=========================================================
ENCAPSULATION IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Encapsulation is the process of bundling data (variables) and methods
(functions) together into a single unit (class) and restricting direct
access to the data.

In simple words:

Data + Functions + Access Control = Encapsulation

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED ENCAPSULATION?
=========================================================

Without Encapsulation:
• Anyone can modify data directly.
• Data can become invalid.
• Poor security.
• High coupling.

Encapsulation provides:
• Data Hiding
• Controlled Access
• Better Security
• Maintainability
• Flexibility

=========================================================
HOW IS ENCAPSULATION ACHIEVED IN C++?
=========================================================

Using:
1. Classes
2. Access Specifiers
   - private
   - protected
   - public

Typically:

Private Data
      ↓
Public Methods (Getter/Setter)
      ↓
Controlled Access

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Employee
{
private:
    int salary;

public:
    void setSalary(int s)
    {
        salary = s;
    }

    int getSalary()
    {
        return salary;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Employee e;

    e.setSalary(50000);

    cout << e.getSalary();
}

Output:
50000

=========================================================
WHY PRIVATE?
=========================================================

Bad Design:

class Employee
{
public:
    int salary;
};

int main()
{
    Employee e;

    e.salary = -5000;
}

Invalid state is possible.

---------------------------------------------------------

Good Design:

class Employee
{
private:
    int salary;

public:
    void setSalary(int s)
    {
        if (s >= 0)
            salary = s;
    }

    int getSalary()
    {
        return salary;
    }
};

Now invalid values can be prevented.

