=========================================================
EXAMPLE OF CONTROLLED ACCESS
=========================================================

class BankAccount
{
private:
    double balance;

public:
    void deposit(double amount)
    {
        if (amount > 0)
            balance += amount;
    }

    void withdraw(double amount)
    {
        if (amount <= balance)
            balance -= amount;
    }
};

User cannot directly modify:

balance

=========================================================
ENCAPSULATION vs DATA HIDING
=========================================================

Encapsulation:
---------------
Binding data and methods together and controlling access.

Data Hiding:
------------
Restricting access to implementation details.

Data Hiding is a subset of Encapsulation.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW TABLE
=========================================================

Feature              Encapsulation      Data Hiding
---------------------------------------------------
Purpose              Bundle + Protect   Restrict Access
Achieved Using       Class + Access     Access Specifiers
Includes Methods     Yes                No
Includes Data        Yes                Yes
Relationship         Parent Concept     Subset

=========================================================
ENCAPSULATION vs ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

Encapsulation:
--------------
How data is protected.

Abstraction:
------------
What functionality is exposed.

Encapsulation:
Implementation level.

Abstraction:
Design level.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Car:

Encapsulation:
Private members:
• Engine
• Fuel System
• Internal Data

Abstraction:
Public Interface:
• Start()
• Stop()
• Accelerate()

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Encapsulation?

Answer:
Encapsulation is the process of bundling data and methods together into
a single unit and restricting direct access to data.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. How is Encapsulation achieved in C++?

Answer:
Using classes and access specifiers (private, protected, public).

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Why do we need Encapsulation?

Answer:
• Data Hiding
• Security
• Controlled Access
• Validation
• Maintainability

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Is private keyword equal to Encapsulation?

Answer:
No.

private is only one mechanism used to implement Encapsulation.

Encapsulation is a broader concept.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Is Data Hiding same as Encapsulation?

Answer:
No.

Data Hiding is a subset of Encapsulation.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Can Encapsulation exist without private members?

Answer:
Yes.

Encapsulation means bundling data and methods together.
private simply strengthens it by restricting access.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. What are the disadvantages of poor encapsulation?

Answer:
• Invalid object states
• High coupling
• Difficult maintenance
• Poor security

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Encapsulation is one of the four pillars of OOP. It is the process of
bundling data and methods into a single unit (class) and controlling
access to the data using access specifiers. It provides data hiding,
security, validation, and better maintainability. In C++, it is
typically achieved by keeping data members private and exposing public
getter/setter methods.

